docs.abstract: Voters overwhelmingly approved a bid to scrap the charter inherited from Gen. Augusto Pinochet’s dictatorship, a move that could set a new course for the country.
docs.snippet: Voters overwhelmingly approved a bid to scrap the charter inherited from Gen. Augusto Pinochet’s dictatorship, a move that could set a new course for the country.
docs.lead_paragraph: SANTIAGO, Chile — The protests started over a small hike in metro fares, then exploded into a broad reckoning over inequality that shook Chile for weeks. Hundreds of thousands of demonstrators poured into the streets, calling for sweeping change in their society, with higher wages and pensions, better health care and education.

headline.main: ‘An End to the Chapter of Dictatorship’: Chileans Vote to Draft a New Constitution
headline.print_headline: Chileans Vote to Rewrite Dictatorship-Era Charter

docs.abstract: In “The Baptism,” Carrie Mae Weems and Carl Hancock Rux find an abstract, elegiac voice in their video honoring John Lewis and C.T. Vivian.
docs.snippet: In “The Baptism,” Carrie Mae Weems and Carl Hancock Rux find an abstract, elegiac voice in their video honoring John Lewis and C.T. Vivian.
docs.lead_paragraph: During the last several months, between the scourge of Covid-19 and the spate of Black deaths resulting from police brutality, Blackness has become a concept loaded with fresh injuries. In “The Baptism,” a short, abstract video tribute to Representative John Lewis and the civil rights leader C.T. Vivian, Blackness isn’t divorced from the tragedies but carefully picked apart and examined through an existential lens. The result is a work that is freeing and radical in a way that Black art so often doesn’t get to be.

headline.main: Black Art and Poetry Elevate a Tribute to Civil Rights Leaders
headline.print_headline: A Tribute Plants Seeds for Everlasting Life

docs.lead_paragraph: LAGOS, Nigeria — With protests breaking out across Nigeria and in expatriate Nigerian communities around the world, the country’s president vowed to a skeptical public on Monday that he would crack down on rogue police officers accused of brutalizing citizens.

headline.main: Nigerians Demand End to Police Squad Known for Brutalizing the Young
headline.print_headline: Protesters Worldwide Demand an End to Nigeria’s Secret Police Squad

docs.abstract: Spurred by recent social unrest, many U.S. companies are trying to make it easier for workers, and urging their customers, to cast their ballots.
docs.snippet: Spurred by recent social unrest, many U.S. companies are trying to make it easier for workers, and urging their customers, to cast their ballots.
docs.lead_paragraph: Bank of America is offering employees up to three hours of paid time to vote this year. The spirits company Diageo North America has declared a no-meeting day on Nov. 3. Best Buy is closing stores until noon that day, and PayPal is offering a half day, paid, to workers who volunteer at polling places.

headline.main: Paid Time Off, Free Fries: How Corporate America Is Getting Out the Vote
headline.print_headline: How Corporate America Is Helping to Get Out the Vote

docs.abstract: An exhibition looks back at a point in the 1970s when the philosopher and activist was a state-promoted hero behind the Iron Curtain.
docs.snippet: An exhibition looks back at a point in the 1970s when the philosopher and activist was a state-promoted hero behind the Iron Curtain.
docs.lead_paragraph: DRESDEN, Germany — The philosopher, feminist and Black liberation activist Angela Davis is everywhere right now. In the wake of Black Lives Matter protests around the world, TV networks, magazines and newspapers have turned to her, drawing on her decades of activism and scholarship to explain the current moment.

headline.main: East Germany’s Love Affair With Angela Davis
